25
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Language Takeaway.

26
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
So the first word we have is vendor.

27
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,000
This is a noun.

28
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:08,000
It means it's a job.

29
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,000
It's the name of a person's job.

30
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:11,000
So he is a vendor.

31
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Okay, and a vendor, what does a vendor do?

32
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Well, a vendor sells things.

33
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Okay, so the verb here is to vend.

34
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Like a vending machine is that machine that you can buy sodas from.

35
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,000
But a vendor is someone who sells things to someone else.

36
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Okay, so I can say he is a door vendor.

37
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:30,000
He sells doors?

38
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Yeah, that's right.

39
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Or let me contact my vendor about the price list for these TVs.

40
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Okay, very good.

41
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,000
So we're talking about a vendor who is going out of business.

42
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And because he's going out of business, this manager is actually looking for a suitable replacement.

43
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
So this is an interesting phrase because these two words normally go together.

44
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
We say, let's find a replacement.

45
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Okay, that's good.

46
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:55,000
But really, we want a suitable replacement.

47
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
And so first of all, the word suitable means like appropriate or good.

48
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:00,000
But what about replacement?

49
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:00,000
What does this mean?

50
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
A replacement is something that takes the place of, it replaces something else.

51
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,000
So for example, we have our vendor who went out of business.

52
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:18,000
So what we are looking now for is another vendor, but not just any vendor, a suitable vendor, one that has the things that we need or the prices that we need.

53
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And in order to replace the one that went out of business.

54
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Right, so we could say this about other things, not just people.

55
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:31,000
For example, if I break my iPhone, my cell phone, very expensive phone, I'm upset about it.

56
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,000
But when I buy a new one, I don't want a cheap one.

57
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
I want a suitable replacement, one that's about the same as the old one.

58
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:37,000
That's right.

59
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:42,000
So maybe you don't get the exact same one, but you get one that's very similar.

60
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Okay, very good.

61
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:56,000
So now they're gonna talk a little bit about the contract, but they kind of do a little bit of small talk and they're talking about coffee and he says, well, you know, I'd be a zombie if I didn't have my morning coffee fix.

62
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:57,000
I know how that feels.

63
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
This is a person who loves to drink caffeine to wake up.

64
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And so we talk about a fix as being something that you need, okay?

65
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:10,000
My coffee fix means the coffee that I drink in the morning to survive.

66
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:11,000
That's right.

67
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:15,000
Okay, so we know the verb to fix is to make something good again, to repair.

68
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
But in this case, we're taking fix as a noun and we're saying that it's something that you need.

69
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Like you said, for example, maybe in the morning you need your English fix and so you'd listen to English pod.

70
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Exactly.

71
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
You need it so much, it's like a drug.

72
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:29,000
That's right.

73
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Very good.

74
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:41,000
And moving on, they started to talk a little bit more about the details of the business and he mentioned that they want to make this company their sole supplier for cameras.

75
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Okay, so sole, S-O-L-E, means only.

76
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
But this word supplier is very interesting because it's very similar to vendor.

77
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:55,000
So it's basically someone, a company maybe, or a person that supplies you with what you need.

78
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:57,000
All right, so to supply is to provide for.

79
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:08,000
So for example, if I work at a clothing store and I sell lots of nice clothing, I need a supplier to bring me the clothes that I sell, otherwise where am I going to get them from?

80
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:09,000
I don't have a factory.

81
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:10,000
That's right.

82
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:15,000
For example, IBM is one of the biggest computer suppliers or manufacturers in the world.

83
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:15,000
All right.

84
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Okay.

85
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:23,000
And for the last part of the dialogue, they said, well, I think we can reach an agreement.

86
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
Let's get started by drafting a new contract.

87
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:28,000
They're going to draft a contract.

88
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
All right, so this is interesting because we don't use the verb to write a contract.

89
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Now you would think, well, of course you write it, but there's a special verb that we use with the word contract.

90
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:45,000
So just remember this phrase together, to draft a contract, or my company will draft a contract and send it to you.

91
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:49,000
This means to prepare a contract in order for someone to sign it.

92
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:49,000
That's right.

93
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:56,000
So it's basically the same as write, but it's usually used more with contracts, to draft a contract.

94
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Exactly.

95
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Or maybe you can say to draft up a business plan.

96
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Exactly.

97
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:07,000
So to draft a plan, to draft a contract, this is basically to write something that has many different points, many different strategies.

98
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:08,000
Okay, very good.

