00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:23,000
So there are a lot of really, really juicy phrases in today's lesson.

104
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
The first one is rest assured.

105
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:28,000
So we heard this from Michael at the beginning of the dialogue.

106
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
He said, rest assured that you can count on us.

107
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:32,000
That's right.

108
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:33,000
Rest assured.

109
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:42,000
So this is a phrase that you use to try to give confidence to someone, telling them, you can trust me, rest assured that I'll be there.

110
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:43,000
Don't worry.

111
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Don't worry.

112
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,000
So let's hear another example of it.

113
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
Rest assured, Marco, I will be there to support you.

114
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:49,000
Okay.

115
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:52,000
So I know that you will be there, or I can trust that you'll be there.

116
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Okay.

117
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Very good.

118
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,000
So to rest assured.

119
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:03,000
Now the second part of it is in that same sentence, well, rest assure that you can count on us.

120
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:04,000
Okay.

121
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
So what does it mean to count on us, to count on me?

122
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:12,000
So the verb to count has a couple of different meanings, and most of us are familiar with the other one.

123
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:13,000
To count numbers.

124
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
One, two, three, four, five.

125
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:24,000
But here, to count on someone, remember that preposition on, means to expect someone to do something, to depend on someone.

126
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:25,000
That's right.

127
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:32,000
So if you count on someone, means that you depend on them, you rely on them, you can trust them.

128
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:41,000
So for example, in the sentence that I just told Marco, rest assured I will be there, you can count on me.

129
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:47,000
That means you can depend on me, you can expect me to be there, I will not let you down.

130
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:48,000
That's right.

131
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Okay.

132
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:52,000
In that same sentence, we have another phrasal verb.

133
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:58,000
Rest assure that you can count on us to be here for the long run.

134
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,000
The long run.

135
00:07:59,000 --> 00:07:59,000
All right.

136
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
So we're not actually running here.

137
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
The long run is a phrase that means for a long time.

138
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:17,000
So for example, if I'm in an interview and someone asks me, well, we're really interested in your, you know, your resume, and we really like you, we want to know, are you available in the long run, in the long term?

139
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:18,000
That's right.

140
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:23,000
So if you say, yes, I am here for the long run, it means that you are here for a long time.

141
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Mm hmm.

142
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:25,000
Okay.

143
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:34,000
And let's move on to our next phrase, when they're actually, you know, they stopped with a small talk, and now they want to get down to business.

144
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:43,000
You hear this phrase all the time, because you don't just walk into a meeting and start talking about business stuff, you know, you start with the nice things first, you say, how was your weekend?

145
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:43,000
How's your wife?

146
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
How was that game of golf?

147
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:53,000
So you're talking about nice, small talk, like you just said, Marco, but when you want to start talking about numbers or products, things like that, that is called business.

148
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,000
So when you want to start that, you say, let's get down to business.

149
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,000
That's right.

150
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Very good.

151
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:06,000
So it's a phrase to say, okay, now let's start talking about what we came here to do, start talking about business.

152
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:11,000
And the last phrase that we have for you, it's a very interesting phrase.

153
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:21,000
When they were talking about one of the brands of phones, they're saying, I'm glad to hear that Pear has finally jumped on the bandwagon.

154
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:26,000
Marco, I wish I could tell you I knew where this phrase came from, but I don't.

155
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:28,000
Let's just talk about the word bandwagon first.

156
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
I think bandwagon means something that everyone is doing.

157
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:34,000
That's right.

158
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:44,000
So I think if everyone is, I don't know, likes the color purple and all of a sudden you like the color purple, then that means you just jumped on the bandwagon.

159
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:45,000
All right.

160
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,000
I jumped on the bandwagon.

161
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:53,000
So you think of a wagon as like, you know, before they had cars, they had wagons, they're wooden and they have wheels and they're pulled by a horse.

162
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,000
And so everyone is on there and they're all going somewhere.

163
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And I wasn't on it, but I jumped on the back.

164
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:00,000
That means I joined everyone.

165
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,000
I started to do what they're doing.

166
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:03,000
That's right.

167
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:08,000
And so I guess you agree with them or you're going towards in the same direction that everyone else is going.

168
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:09,000
Look at Marco.

169
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:10,000
He just bought an iPhone.

170
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:11,000
Now he's jumped on the bandwagon.

171
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:12,000
That's right.

172
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:14,000
So everyone is going in the same direction.

173
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:16,000
Everyone is doing the same thing.

174
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,000
Everyone likes the same thing.

175
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:33,000
So to jump on the bandwagon, you can use it in the business sense, for example, if somebody is not agreeing with you or somebody doesn't want to support your project, you can say, I would really appreciate it if you jumped on the bandwagon and supported us on this.

176
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:33,000
That's right.

177
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:42,000
So it's not always a bad thing, but remember that the verb that is synonymous with this is to conform, okay, to do what everyone else is doing.

178
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:43,000
That's right.

179
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:43,000
Okay.

